RSTUDIO PROJECT CHEAT SHEET (Data collection + description + 2 statistical tests)

0) Recommended project structure
  project/
    data_raw/                 raw collected data (never overwrite)
    data_clean/               cleaned datasets (csv)
    R/                        reusable functions (cleaning, plots, tests)
    outputs/
      figures/                png/pdf plots
      tables/                 csv/tex tables
    report/                   .Rmd or Quarto file
    README.md                 what you did + how to run

1) RStudio setup and daily workflow
  Create project: File > New Project > Existing Directory (or New Directory)
  Use scripts: File > New File > R Script (analysis.R, cleaning.R, plots.R)
  Use R Markdown: File > New File > R Markdown (report.Rmd)
  Working directory: use Projects, avoid setwd() in scripts
  Restart R: Session > Restart R
  Install packages once:
    install.packages(c("tidyverse","lubridate","janitor","broom","here","skimr","ggpubr"))
  Load packages each session:
    library(tidyverse); library(lubridate); library(janitor); library(broom); library(here)

2) Reproducibility essentials
  Seed for randomness (only if you simulate):
    set.seed(123)
  Never edit raw data files. Save cleaned data separately.
  Use here() for file paths:
    readr::read_csv(here("data_raw","file.csv"))
    readr::write_csv(df, here("data_clean","df_clean.csv"))
  Record decisions:
    keep a short data dictionary: column name, unit, meaning, allowed values

3) Data collection patterns (choose one)
  A) Manual observations (Västtrafik delays)
    Collect: planned_time, actual_arrival, line, mode (bus/tram), date, time_of_day, rush (0/1)
    Tip: log in a consistent format (ISO date time). One row per departure.

  B) Store price basket (Willys vs Hemköp)
    Collect: item_id, item_name, chain, store, date, price_sek, size_g_ml, organic (0/1)
    Tip: same item_id across chains for paired comparisons. One row per item per store.

  C) Surveys
    Collect: respondent_id, age_group, category answers (Likert), etc.
    Tip: export csv, do not change the export manually. Clean in R.

4) Import, clean, validate (typical commands)
  Import:
    df_raw <- readr::read_csv(here("data_raw","mydata.csv"))
  Clean column names:
    df <- janitor::clean_names(df_raw)
  Convert types:
    df <- df |>
      mutate(date = as.Date(date),
             planned_time = lubridate::ymd_hms(planned_time),
             actual_time = lubridate::ymd_hms(actual_time))
  Create derived variables:
    df <- df |>
      mutate(delay_min = as.numeric(difftime(actual_time, planned_time, units="mins")),
             late_3min = delay_min > 3)
  Basic validation checks:
    summary(df)
    anyNA(df)
    dplyr::count(df, mode)
    stopifnot(all(df$delay_min > -60 & df$delay_min < 180, na.rm=TRUE))

5) Descriptive statistics (minimum requirements)
  Quick overview:
    skimr::skim(df)
  Group summaries:
    df |>
      group_by(mode) |>
      summarise(n = n(),
                mean_delay = mean(delay_min, na.rm=TRUE),
                sd_delay = sd(delay_min, na.rm=TRUE),
                median_delay = median(delay_min, na.rm=TRUE),
                iqr_delay = IQR(delay_min, na.rm=TRUE))

6) Plots (ggplot2 patterns)
  Histogram / density:
    ggplot(df, aes(delay_min)) + geom_histogram() + theme_minimal()
  Boxplot by group:
    ggplot(df, aes(mode, delay_min)) + geom_boxplot() + theme_minimal()
  Bar plot of proportions (late vs on time):
    df |>
      count(mode, late_3min) |>
      group_by(mode) |>
      mutate(prop = n / sum(n)) |>
      ggplot(aes(mode, prop, fill = late_3min)) + geom_col() + theme_minimal()

  Save plot:
    ggsave(here("outputs","figures","box_delay_by_mode.png"), width=7, height=4)

7) Statistical tests (choose two, aligned with hypothesis)
  A) Two sample t test (bus vs tram mean delay)
    t.test(delay_min ~ mode, data=df, var.equal=FALSE)   # Welch t test default
    Report: t, df, p, mean difference, CI

  Assumptions to check:
    independence by design (different departures)
    approximate normality (hist, QQ plot) or rely on CLT if n large
    unequal variances -> Welch is fine

  B) Chi square test (late proportions differ by mode)
    tab <- table(df$mode, df$late_3min)
    chisq.test(tab)           # expects adequate expected counts
    If expected counts small:
      fisher.test(tab)

  C) Paired t test (same items, two stores)
    df_wide <- df |>
      select(item_id, chain, price_sek) |>
      tidyr::pivot_wider(names_from=chain, values_from=price_sek)
    t.test(df_wide$Willys, df_wide$Hemkop, paired=TRUE)

  D) Regression (predict price or delay)
    model <- lm(price_sek ~ size_g_ml + organic + chain, data=df)
    summary(model)
    broom::tidy(model)
    plot(model)               # residual diagnostics

8) Effect size and confidence intervals (stronger report)
  Mean difference CI from t test is already provided.
  Cohen’s d (manual quick idea):
    d = (mean1 - mean2) / pooled_sd
  For proportions difference:
    report risk difference or odds ratio (optional).

9) Writing the research report (Rmd skeleton)
  Sections to include:
    Title + research question + hypothesis (H0/H1)
    Data collection method (how, where, when, sample size, inclusion rules)
    Variables + units + how derived (delay_min, late_3min, basket_total, etc.)
    Descriptive stats + plots (at least 2 plots)
    Test 1: method, assumptions, results, interpretation
    Test 2: method, assumptions, results, interpretation
    Limitations (sampling bias, measurement error, confounding, independence)
    Conclusion + what you would do next

  R Markdown workflow:
    Knit to PDF/HTML: "Knit" button
    Use code chunks with set.seed if simulating
    Keep output objects: save tables as csv, figures as png

10) Common mistakes to avoid
  Mixing up independence: repeated measures on same item or same route needs paired or clustered approach.
  p value fishing: decide hypothesis and tests before looking at results.
  Units confusion: minutes vs seconds, grams vs kg.
  Editing raw data in Excel: do not. Clean in R.
  Using too small sample sizes for chi square: use Fisher if needed.

11) Quick templates for the two example projects

  Västtrafik delays
    Data columns (minimum):
      date_time, mode (bus/tram), line, planned_time, actual_time, rush (0/1)
    Derived:
      delay_min, late_3min
    Tests:
      Welch two sample t test on delay_min by mode
      Chi square (or Fisher) on mode x late_3min

  Store basket prices
    Data columns (minimum):
      item_id, item_name, chain, store, date, price_sek, size_g_ml, organic (0/1)
    Derived:
      price_per_unit = price_sek / size_g_ml
    Tests:
      Paired t test on matched items across chains
      Regression of price_per_unit on organic + chain + size_g_ml

12) Minimal package set for most student projects
  tidyverse, lubridate, janitor, broom, here, skimr

